As public and private schools in Rivers State resume for the second term 2019/2020 academic session today, the state government has directed the 437 private schools that did not meet set requirements, to stop operations forthwith. Recall that governor, Nyesom Ezenwo Wike, had set up a Committee for Accreditation and Approval of Private Schools; a move designed to improve quality education in the state. The committee, headed by the vice-chancellor of Ignatius Ajuru University of Education, Professor Ozo Mekuri Ndimele, had in its report denied accreditation/approval to 437 schools which did not meet set requirements for the operations of private schools. Speaking with newsmen in Port Harcourt, the commissioner for education, Professor Kaniye Ebeku, said the directive on the ban of unapproved schools still subsists. Ebeku advised parents and guardians of pupils and students not to patronize unapproved schools, adding that such schools are illegal and should not resume.
The commissioner warned that anyone caught operating unapproved schools in the state will face appropriate sanctions of the law. He stated that the state government has made adequate provisions for the maintenance and functioning of public schools in the state. Ebeku, who cautioned heads of public primary and secondary schools in the state not collect any fee from pupils and students, stated that any Principal or Head teacher that violates the directive will face appropriate disciplinary measures.